                <h3>The U.S. National Plant Germplasm System - An Overview</h3>
                <p>
                    The USDA-ARS National Plant Germplasm System (NPGS) is among the largest, most diverse collections of plant genetic resources in the world. The NPGS safeguards irreplaceable plant genetic resources in genebank units across 20 geographical locations, often in partnership with land-grant universities.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <img src="https://www.ars-grin.gov/assets/img/NPGS_Hardiness_Map.png" alt="NPGS Hardiness Map" border="0" usemap="#hardinessMap" />
                    NPGS maintains collections of more than 200 crops at sites best suited to the biological
                    and environmental needs of each. This map shows the NPGS genebank units overlayed onto the
                    2023 USDA Plant Hardiness Zone Map.

                    NPGS collections include crops with agricultural importance for food, fiber, animal
                    feed, industrial, medicinal, and ornamental purposes.

                    The NPGS currently maintains over 620,000 accessions, representing more than 16,000 species.
                </p>

