                <p>
                    As part of its mission, the NPGS maintains, characterizes, evaluates, documents,
                    enhances, and distributes plant genetic resources and associated information.
                    Materials from the NPGS are identified by PI (Plant Identification) numbers,
                    which are up to six digits in length. Local site identifiers might also be used.
                    NPGS collection information is available through GRIN-Global, an
                    information management system accessed online.

                    The types of information available for NPGS accessions include passport, taxonomy,
                    trait and genetic data, images, and many more.
                </p>
                <p>
                    As one the largest distributors of plant genetic resources in the world, an average
                    of over 200,000 NPGS samples are distributed annually for research, breeding,
                    and educational purposes. The NPGS also conducts applied research to identify
                    more efficient and effective management procedures for plant genetic resources,
                    to add value to collections by performing trait evaluations and generating or
                    collecting genetic/genomic data.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Collections include <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/landrace" target="_blank">landraces</a>
                    of crops that have emerged over millennia of improvement by farmers; wild plants
                    related to cultivated crops; older and current crop varieties; parental breeding
                    lines; specialized plant materials used to develop new varieties and hybrids;
                    or mutant genetic stocks maintained for research. Germplasm can be preserved as
                    plants growing in greenhouse, screenhouse, field plantings, or as <i>in vitro</i>
                    cultures.
                    Dried seeds of many species can be stored at low temperatures in sealed containers
                    for many years (orthodox seeds). Plants that produce desiccation-intolerant seeds
                    (recalcitrant seeds), or those that can only be propagated clonally, might be maintained
                    <i>in vitro</i>, as cultures of tissues, or as buds, pollen or other plant parts
                    preserved at ultra-low temperatures.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Plant breeders rely on plant genetic resources to develop new crop varieties
                    that are more nutritious, have higher yields, resilience to extreme weather,
                    and resistance to pests and diseases. In many cases, the NPGS provides the
                    initial sources of plant genes that ultimately benefit consumers and ensure
                    food security for the U.S. The process of crop development from wild species
                    to food and improved products for the consumer is a continuous challenge.

                    The development of high-performing varieties for the market involves surmounting
                    the challenges of pests, diseases, changing and highly variable climatic conditions,
                    and economic hardships. Breeders and product developers continually and frequently
                    access germplasm from the NPGS for their innovations and inventions.
                    Consumers greatly benefit from the foundation of plant genetic material
                    available from the NPGS.
                </p>
                <p>
                    For example, the NPGS peanut accession
                    <a href="https://npgsweb.ars-grin.gov/gringlobal/accessiondetail?id=1170633" target="_blank">PI 203396</a>,
                    originally from Brazil has resistance to
                    <a href="https://www.clemson.edu/public/regulatory/plant-problem/fact-sheets/tswv.html" target="_blank">Tomato Spotted Wilt Virus (TSWV)</a>.
                    It was used in breeding programs to produce commercially viable lines with TSWV resistance.
                    The economic value of the TSWV resistance conferred from PI 203396 is estimated to be more than
                    $200M per year.

                    Other examples of the many impacts of the NPGS can be found in our
                    eBook, “<a href="https://colostate.pressbooks.pub/pgrsuccessstories/" target="_blank">Plant Genetic Resources: Success Stories</a>”.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Globally, the diversity of plant genetic resources has diminished. Native habitats are
                    destroyed by human activities and by environmental change. Wild species of plants become
                    extinct, and traditional landraces disappear along with traditional peoples and their
                    knowledge. Heritage cultivars are lost. Genetic and corresponding cultural information
                    must be preserved. Genebank collections that are threatened by political or institutional
                    instability must be safeguarded. The ability to acquire and exchange resources,
                    increasingly restricted by numerous factors, can be facilitated by international agreements.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The NPGS is primarily federally funded through the U.S. Department of Agriculture,
                    but also receives key financial and in-kind support from Land-Grant Universities, <a href="https://www.nifa.usda.gov/grants/programs/capacity-grants/state-agricultural-experiment-stations" target="_blank">State Agricultural Experiment Stations</a>
                    and agricultural industries.
                </p>
